Classification with K Nearest Neighbours (KNN)

For DATA50XX by ctong

Overview

What Is KNN?

K Nearest Neighbours (KNN) is a simple, intuitive machine learning method used for classification and regression. In classification, KNN predicts the category of a new observation based on the categories of its closest data points in the training set.

How Does KNN Work?

  1. Lazy Learning Algorithm: No real learning. KNN does not build a model ahead of time. It stores the training data and defers computation until prediction is needed. It does not learn anything from the data in advance.

  2. Measure Distance: To predict class for a new observation, KNN represents the feature values as a point in n-dimensional space and calculates the distance to every training point (commonly Euclidean distance).

  3. Find the K Nearest Neighbours: It selects the K closest training points.

  4. Vote: The most frequent class among these neighbours becomes the predicted class.

Choosing the Right Value of K

  • Small K (e.g., 1) can be sensitive to noise.
  • Large K smooths predictions but may overlook local patterns.
  • Use cross-validation to choose K.

Key Considerations

Sensitivity to irrelevant features

KNN treats all features equally. Irrelevant features can distort measures of similarity.

Scale distortion

Features must be on similar scales to avoid dominance by features on larger scales. Solution: Normalize (rescale to [0,1]) or Standardize (convert to z scores)

Flexible decision boundaries
  • Pro: Captures complex patterns.
  • Con: Can overfit if K is too small or data is noisy.
Computationally expensive

KNN does not train a model it stores the data and compares new inputs to all training points when making predictions. This can be very slow and memory-heavy on large datasets.

Curse of Dimensionality

KNN may perform poorly with a large number of features. When there is a large number of dimensions, all points become far apart. The measure of distance becomes less meaningful, making it harder to find patterns. This is sometimes referred to as the curse of dimensionality. Proper feature selection is important before applying KNN for classification. KNN typically performs adequately with fewer than 10 features and it is generally recommended that the number of features be less than the square root of the number of observations in a data set to avoid overfitting.

Cross-Validation with data preprocessing

set.seed(123)
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
knn_model <- train(diabetes ~ ., 
                   data = df,
                   method = "knn",
                   trControl = ctrl,
                   preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
                   tuneLength = 20) 

print(knn_model)

  • Kappa: A measure of agreement between predicted and actual classes that adjusts for chance agreement.
